




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Choice of Techniques and the Optimality of Market Equilibrium with Rational Expectations
AU  - Stiglitz, Joseph E.
Y1  - 1982/04/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261054
DO  - 10.1086/261054
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 223
EP  - 246
VL  - 90
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper shows that, in the absence of a complete set of risk markets, prices provide incorrect signals for guiding production decisions. Even if all individuals have rational expectations concerning the distribution of prices which will prevail on the market next period, the market allocation is, in general, not a constrained Pareto optimum. Essentially the only conditions under which, for all technologies, the market equilibrium is a constrained Pareto optimum are those in which risk markets are redundant. We derive the necessary and sufficient conditions for redundancy of risk markets, which turn out to be extremely restrictive.
AB  - This paper shows that, in the absence of a complete set of risk markets, prices provide incorrect signals for guiding production decisions. Even if all individuals have rational expectations concerning the distribution of prices which will prevail on the market next period, the market allocation is, in general, not a constrained Pareto optimum. Essentially the only conditions under which, for all technologies, the market equilibrium is a constrained Pareto optimum are those in which risk markets are redundant. We derive the necessary and sufficient conditions for redundancy of risk markets, which turn out to be extremely restrictive.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261054
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261054
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Monetary Policy and the Information Content of Prices
AU  - King, Robert G.
Y1  - 1982/04/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261055
DO  - 10.1086/261055
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 247
EP  - 279
VL  - 90
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Rational expectations and cleared markets lead to the proposition that feedback monetary policy is irrelevant to real activity, as in the analyses of Sargent and Wallace. However, if agents are differentially informed and have access to a common price, then prospective monetary policy actions--future feedback to imperfectly known current circumstances--can alter real activity by changing the information content of prices.
AB  - Rational expectations and cleared markets lead to the proposition that feedback monetary policy is irrelevant to real activity, as in the analyses of Sargent and Wallace. However, if agents are differentially informed and have access to a common price, then prospective monetary policy actions--future feedback to imperfectly known current circumstances--can alter real activity by changing the information content of prices.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261055
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261055
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Waiting-Line Auctions
AU  - Holt,, Charles A.
AU  - Sherman, Roger
Y1  - 1982/04/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261056
DO  - 10.1086/261056
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 280
EP  - 294
VL  - 90
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - If prizes are to be awarded simultaneously at a specified time on a first-come- first-served basis, then individuals who queue for them will choose different waiting times through their arrivals at the queue. This choice of arrival time at a queue is similar to the choice of a sealed tender in an auction. An equilibrium for this "waiting-line auction" is obtained here using methods for analyzing sealed-tender auctions. When individuals are risk neutral it is shown that several alternative waiting-line allocation procedures result in the same transactions cost associated with waiting in line.
AB  - If prizes are to be awarded simultaneously at a specified time on a first-come- first-served basis, then individuals who queue for them will choose different waiting times through their arrivals at the queue. This choice of arrival time at a queue is similar to the choice of a sealed tender in an auction. An equilibrium for this "waiting-line auction" is obtained here using methods for analyzing sealed-tender auctions. When individuals are risk neutral it is shown that several alternative waiting-line allocation procedures result in the same transactions cost associated with waiting in line.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261056
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261056
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Seigniorage and the Case for a National Money
AU  - Fischer, Stanley
Y1  - 1982/04/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261057
DO  - 10.1086/261057
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 295
EP  - 313
VL  - 90
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In countries with high rates of inflation there is typically movement away from the use of the local currency. The paper analyzes the costs and benefits of using a local currency, with emphasis on the seigniorage foregone by using a foreign money. Even if it should be desirable for a country to fix its exchange rate, it still loses seigniorage if it does not use its own money. The case for using a foreign money then turns largely on the superior discipline imposed on domestic policymakers by removing their control over the money supply. Alternative methods of imposing discipline are discussed. Estimates of the amount of seigniorage raised by different governments are presented; seigniorage amounts in some cases to about 10 percent of government revenue. Estimates are also presented of both the annual flow and one-time stock costs of giving up use of domestic currencies and instead using the dollar. The flow cost is typically about 1 percent of GNP and the stock cost is around 10 percent of GNP.
AB  - In countries with high rates of inflation there is typically movement away from the use of the local currency. The paper analyzes the costs and benefits of using a local currency, with emphasis on the seigniorage foregone by using a foreign money. Even if it should be desirable for a country to fix its exchange rate, it still loses seigniorage if it does not use its own money. The case for using a foreign money then turns largely on the superior discipline imposed on domestic policymakers by removing their control over the money supply. Alternative methods of imposing discipline are discussed. Estimates of the amount of seigniorage raised by different governments are presented; seigniorage amounts in some cases to about 10 percent of government revenue. Estimates are also presented of both the annual flow and one-time stock costs of giving up use of domestic currencies and instead using the dollar. The flow cost is typically about 1 percent of GNP and the stock cost is around 10 percent of GNP.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261057
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261057
Y2  - 2024/03/22
